<dl id="n42022e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42022e">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42022e"> 22(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> to the best of / his memory <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42022e"><li>FW 240.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kd/lexkd.htm#n42022e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kd/l39kd.htm#n42022e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42022e">MS BL 47477-75</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:95 <a name="kdd2" href="../../ff/fdra/kda.htm#kdd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kd/kdd2.htm#n42022e">Draft: II.1&sect;4.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">If the law which says to every sinner: &ldquo;You are bound, under pain of eternal damnation, to remember all your bad thoughts and confess them to the best of your memory,&rdquo; were not so evidently a satanic invention, it ought to be put among the most infamous ideas which have ever come out of the brain of fallen man. <small> Chiniquy, <a name="CPWC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CPWC"><cite title="source">The Priest The Woman and The Confessional</cite></a> (n.d.) 108</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
